<div class="row g-4"><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><h2 id="monohybrid-crosses">Monohybrid Crosses</h2><ul><li><p>Monohybrid inheritance looks at how the <b>alleles for a single gene are passed on from one generation to the next</b></p></li><li><p>Known information about the <b>genotypes</b>, <b>phenotypes</b> and the process of <b>meiosis</b> are used to make <b>predictions </b>about the phenotypes of offspring that would result from specific breeding pairs</p></li><li><p>When two individuals <b>sexually reproduce</b> there is an equal chance of either allele from their homologous pair making it into their gametes and subsequently the nucleus of the zygote</p><ul><li><p>This means there is an <b>equal chance of the zygote inheriting either allele from their parent</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>Genetic diagrams are often used to present this information in a clear and precise manner so that predictions can be made</p><ul><li><p>These diagrams include a characteristic table called a <b>Punnett square</b></p></li></ul></li><li><p>The predicted genotypes that genetic diagrams produce are all based on <b>chance</b></p><ul><li><p>There is no way to predict which gametes will fuse so sometimes the observed or real-life results can differ from the predictions</p></li></ul></li></ul><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="F1 genetic cross" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="1111" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="F1-genetic-cross.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/01/F1-genetic-cross.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><p class="text-center"><i><b>Genetic crosses can be shown by a Punnet square</b></i></p></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="worked-example"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M3 17.25V21h3.75L17.81 9.94l-3.75-3.75L3 17.25zM20.71 7.04a.996.996 0 0 0 0-1.41l-2.34-2.34a.996.996 0 0 0-1.41 0l-1.83 1.83 3.75 3.75 1.83-1.83z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Worked Example</h4></header><h4 id="worked-example-genetic-diagram">Worked example: Genetic diagram</h4><ul><li><p>One of the genes for the coat colour of horses has the following two alleles:</p><ul><li><p><b>B</b>, a <span class="popovers" data-content="An allele that expresses itself in the phenotype in heterozygous organisms." data-title="Dominant" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">dominant</span> allele produces a black coat when present</p></li><li><p><b>b</b>, a <span class="popovers" data-content="An allele that does not express itself in the phenotype in heterozygous organisms." data-title="Recessive" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">recessive</span> allele produces a chestnut coat when present in a <span class="popovers" data-content="Situation or organism in which paired alleles are the same." data-title="Homozygous" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition">homozygous</span> individual</p></li></ul></li><li><p>In this example a <span class="popovers" data-content="Situation or organism in which paired alleles are different." data-title="Heterozygous" data-toggle="popover" data-type="definition"><b>heterozygous</b></span> <b>male</b> is crossed with <b>heterozygous</b> <b>female</b></p></li></ul><p>Parental phenotype: Black coat x Black coat</p><p>Parental genotypes: Bb x Bb</p><p>Parental gametes: B or b x B or b</p></div></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W"><p class="text-center"><b>Monohybrid Punnett square with Heterozygotes Table</b></p><div class="mb-5" data-type="image"><img alt="Monohybrid Punnett Square with Heterozygotes Table" class="ContentBlock_figure__6whpf" data-nimg="1" decoding="async" height="444" loading="lazy" sizes="(max-width: 320px) 320w, (max-width: 640px) 640w, (max-width: 960px) 960w, (max-width: 1280px) 1280w, 1920w" src="Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png" srcset="https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=16/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 16w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=32/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 32w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=48/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 48w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=64/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 64w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=96/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 96w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=128/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 128w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=256/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 256w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=384/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 384w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=640/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 640w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=750/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 750w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=828/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 828w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1080/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 1080w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1200/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 1200w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=1920/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 1920w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=2048/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 2048w, https://cdn.savemyexams.com/cdn-cgi/image/f=auto,width=3840/https://cdn.savemyexams.com/uploads/2020/11/Monohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-TableMonohybrid-Punnett-Square-with-Heterozygotes-Table.png 3840w" style="color:transparent" width="1100"/></div><ul><li><p>Predicted <b>ratio of phenotypes i</b>n offspring – 3 black coat : 1 chestnut coat</p></li><li><p>Predicted <b>ratio of genotypes </b>in offspring – 1 BB : 2 Bb : 1 bb</p></li></ul></div></div><div class="col-12"><div class="Wrapper_wrapper__raXe4 Card_card__7rJy4 bg-body-secondary rounded-3 p-4 card position-relative ContentBlock_content__MOc3W" data-type="callout"><div class="ContentBlock_callout___oem_" data-variant="exam-tip"><header class="mb-3"><span class="ContentBlock_calloutIcon__XHWM5"><svg aria-hidden="true" class="Icon_icon__caLMg Icon_xl__PzZaA" focusable="false" height="24" viewbox="0 0 24 24" width="24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path d="M9 21c0 .5.4 1 1 1h4c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-1H9v1zm3-19C8.1 2 5 5.1 5 9c0 2.4 1.2 4.5 3 5.7V17c0 .5.4 1 1 1h6c.6 0 1-.5 1-1v-2.3c1.8-1.3 3-3.4 3-5.7 0-3.9-3.1-7-7-7z"></path></svg></span><h4 class="h5">Examiner Tips and Tricks</h4></header><p>You need to be able to interpret genetic diagrams so take some time to get familiar with different sorts of diagrams such as pedigree charts and Punnet squares.</p></div></div></div></div>